After that, there is still only one option to make a1​ become zero, and so on. Thus in this case the answer can be uniquely determined. 106.body: Now, consider we move x from position n−1 to 0, which is a0′​=a0​+x and an−1′​=an−1​−x, the prefix sum array will change to bi′​=bi​+x for 0≤i≤n−2, while the last item bn−1′​=bn−1​=0 stays unchanged. Note that wn−1​=0, so the answer won’t change even if we change bn−1​ to any arbitrary number. Define f(x) be the answer if we move x from position n−1 to 0 (e.g. the above formula is f(0)), we can calculate f(x) as follows: f(x)=0≤i≤n−1∑​∣bi​+x∣⋅wi​ Since the function fi​(x)=∣bi​+x∣⋅wi​ is (non-strictly) convex function, and the summation of convex functions is still convex, we have yielded that f(x) is convex. Using tenary search is enough to pass and get AC. Time Complexity: O(nlog(nC)), where C=1000 is the maximum value of ai​.

107.body:
We can reformat the problem as follows: There are wi​ people on coordinate bi​, find a position x that minimize the sum of distances to every person. Proof.
The sum of distances is ∑∣bi​−x∣⋅wi​, which is exactly f(−x). For any position x that has more people on the left (denoted as pL​) than on the right (denoted as pR​), moving left by 1 will make the sum decreases by pL​−pR​. Vice versa, if pL​<pR​, then moving right will always be better. It is easy to see that the optimal position x is the median of these people. Thus, if we sort (bi​,wi​) by increasing bi​, and calculate the position of the weighted median, we can get the optimal x without any call to f(⋅), and get AC with only one call to f(−x). Time Complexity: O(nlogn) (for sorting).

Then, to calculate the answer for [ql,qr], you can start from [1,n] and employ Divide and Conquer once more. During the recursion, for the current interval [l,r] and the queried interval [ql,qr], there are three situations: [l,r] is entirely inside [ql,qr]. In this case, we can directly add sum([l,r]) to our answer. [l,r] is entirely outside [ql,qr]. In this scenario, this interval doesn't affect the answer. Otherwise, we can divide it into two subproblems: How the answer of the interval [l,m] contributes to sum([ql,qr]). How the answer of the interval [m+1,r] contributes to sum([ql,qr]). 在已知每個區間答案的情況下，可以用以上的方法，利用已儲存的部分來求得 [ql,qr] 的答案。就如同題敘提到的，我們分成三個 Case 去分治求解。 參考一下程式碼及註解： 區間查詢，程式碼 long long QuerySum(int &ql, int &qr, int l = 1, int r = n, int idx = 1) { /*** Case 1 : [l, r] is entirely inside [ql, qr] ***/ if (ql <= l && r <= qr) { // contain by query range return intervals[idx].sum; } /*** Case 2 : [l, r] is entirely outside [ql, qr] ***/ if (qr < l || r < ql) { return 0; // return 0 won't affect the calculation of sum in parent query } /*** Case 3 : divide [l, r] into two subproblems ***/ int m = (l + r) / 2; // divide long long left_part_ans = QuerySum(ql, qr, l, m, LEFT_CHILD(idx)); // conquer left part long long right_part_ans = QuerySum(ql, qr, m + 1, r, RIGHT_CHILD(idx)); // conquer right part return left_part_ans + right_part_ans; // merge the result of left and right part
}

Treat updates as a range query of [k,k]. The path of the range query traverses through intervals whose values will be affected if the number changes to u, and we can handle this efficiently. 對於修改的操作，我們要找到所有受修改影響的區間，並更新其答案。 而受影響的區間跟查詢 [k,k] 的過程中遇到的區間一樣，在過程中更新這些區間即可。 參考以下程式碼及註解： 修改操作，程式碼 void UpdateIntervalSum(int k, int u, int l = 1, int r = n, int idx = 1) { // Treat updates as a range query of [k, k] : ql = qr = k /*** Case 1 : [l, r] == [k, k] ***/ if (k <= l && r <= k) { // leaf node, same as (l == k && r == k) intervals[idx].sum = u; return; } /*** Case 2 : [l, r] is entirely outside [k, k] ***/ if (k < l || k > r) // not affected by update return; /*** Case 3 : affected by update, divide [l, r] into two parts ***/ int m = (l + r) / 2; // divide Update(k, u, l, m, LEFT_CHILD(idx)); // conquer left part Update(k, u, m + 1, r, RIGHT_CHILD(idx)); // conquer right part // Update the sum of current interval by merging the result of left and right part intervals[idx].sum = intervals[LEFT_CHILD(idx)].sum + intervals[RIGHT_CHILD(idx)].sum;

In this case, we can directly add sum([l,r]) to our answer. [l,r] is entirely outside [ql,qr]. In this scenario, this interval doesn't affect the answer. Otherwise, we can divide it into two subproblems: How the answer of the interval [l,m] contributes to sum([ql,qr]). How the answer of the interval [m+1,r] contributes to sum([ql,qr]). With the knowledge of the answers for each interval, we can utilize the previously stored information to determine the answer for [ql,qr] using the mentioned method. As the problem statement suggests, we divide the solution into three cases to efficiently apply the divide-and-conquer approach. Take a look at the code and comments for reference: Code: Range Query long long QuerySum(int &ql, int &qr, int l = 1, int r = n, int idx = 1) { /*** Case 1 : [l, r] is entirely inside [ql, qr] ***/ if (ql <= l && r <= qr) { // contain by query range return intervals[idx].sum; } /*** Case 2 : [l, r] is entirely outside [ql, qr] ***/ if (qr < l || r < ql) { return 0; // return 0 won't affect the calculation of sum in parent query } /*** Case 3 : divide [l, r] into two subproblems ***/ int m = (l + r) / 2; // divide long long left_part_ans = QuerySum(ql, qr, l, m, LEFT_CHILD(idx)); // conquer left part long long right_part_ans = QuerySum(ql, qr, m + 1, r, RIGHT_CHILD(idx)); // conquer right part return left_part_ans + right_part_ans; // merge the result of left and right part
}

To get 62 points, we can use binary search on answer. The answer is either in a[] or in b[], so we can just do binary search twice. How to know how many numbers are smaller than a[p]? In the array a[], there are p number smaller than a[p], namely, a[0],a[1],…,a[p−1]. In the array b[], we can use std::upper_bound to find the number of elements greater than a[p]. This method uses about 2log2n compares, which is enough to get 62 points. Sample Code Number two_increasing_arrays(int n, int k, vector<Number> a, vector<Number> b) { --k; for (int lo = 0, hi = n-1, mi; lo <= hi; ) { mi = (lo + hi) >> 1; int small_a = mi; int small_b = lower_bound(begin(b), end(b), a[mi]) - begin(b); if (small_a + small_b == k) return a[mi]; if (small_a + small_b < k) lo = mi + 1; else hi = mi - 1; } for (int lo = 0, hi = n-1, mi; lo <= hi; ) { mi = (lo + hi) >> 1; int small_a = lower_bound(begin(a), end(a), b[mi]) - begin(a); int small_b = mi; if (small_a + small_b == k) return b[mi]; if (small_a + small_b < k) lo = mi + 1; else hi = mi - 1; }

174.body: 要達到滿分，需要得出一個重要的觀察： k 的倍數部分被模 p 也沒差，但如果餘數部分被模 p，就會無法產生正確的貢獻。 不妨將待相乘的數字表達成 ⟨a,q⟩，代表 ak+q，其中 0≤q<k。觀察兩組數字 ⟨a,q⟩ 跟 ⟨b,r⟩ 相乘的結果： (ak+q)(bk+r)=abk2+(ar+bq)k+qr=(abk+ar+bq)k+qr(1-1) 這樣我們就能將 ⟨a,q⟩⋅⟨b,r⟩ 表示成 ⟨(abk+ar+bq)modp,qr⟩ 了！ 而最後的結果 ⟨a′,q′⟩ 的答案就是 (a′+⌊kq′​⌋)modp。 不過，當 k>2 時，q′ 可能會變得超級大，我們勢必也需要在計算中對餘數做些處理。 而餘數可以再次表示成 ck+s 的形式貢獻到商裡面，所以 (1-1) 可以再變成如下算式： (abk+ar+bq)k+qr=(abk+ar+bq+⌊kqr​⌋)k+(qrmodk)(1-2) 也就是說， ⟨a,q⟩⋅⟨b,r⟩=⟨(abk+ar+bq+⌊kqr​⌋)modp,qrmodk⟩ 如此一來，我們也保證了餘數會在 [0,k) 的範圍內，兩數相乘也不會超出 64-bit 整數的範圍。

175.body: 首先，考慮如何計算 ⌊ka​⌋modp，即 ⌊ka​⌋ 除以 p 的餘數。 假設 ⌊ka​⌋ 除以 p 的商是 q、⌊ka​⌋ 除以 p 的餘數是 r，所求為 r。 ⌊ka​⌋=qp+r(2-1) 根據除法定理，我們有 a=⌊ka​⌋⋅k+(amodk)(2-2) 將 (2-1) 代入 (2-2)： a​=(qp+r)⋅k+(amodk)=qpk+rk+(amodk)​ 為了得到 r，注意到 a≡rk+(amodk)(modpk) 由於 rk+(amodk)<rk+k=(r+1)k≤pk，這表示右式即為 a 除以 pk 的餘數： amodpk=rk+(amodk) 注意到上式是 等號。由於 (amodk)<k，計算 r 的方法是直接將 rk+(amodk) 除以 k，商就是答案： ⌊krk+(amodk)​⌋=r+⌊kamodk​⌋=r 換句話說： r=⌊kamodpk​⌋ 回到原問題 ⌊kxy​⌋modp，根據上式可以得出： ⌊kxy​⌋modp=⌊kxymodpk​⌋ 實作上，在計算 xy 的時候改成對 pk 取模，以避免 overflow。 但 pk 的最大值接近 long long 範圍的最大值，在快速冪的過程中需使用 __int128，才能避免兩數相乘時發生 overflow，得出錯誤的結果。

178.body: To achieve a perfect score, an important observation needs to be made: The multiple-of-k part doesn't matter when modulo p, but if the remainder part is taken modulo p, it will not contribute to the answer correctly. Let's express the numbers to be multiplied as ⟨a,q⟩, representing ak+q, where 0≤q<k. Observe the result of multiplying two sets of numbers ⟨a,q⟩ and ⟨b,r⟩: (ak+q)(bk+r)=abk2+(ar+bq)k+qr=(abk+ar+bq)k+qr(1-1) This way, we can represent ⟨a,q⟩⋅⟨b,r⟩ as ⟨(abk+ar+bq)modp,qr⟩! The final result ⟨a′,q′⟩ is then given by (a′+⌊kq′​⌋)modp. However, when k>2, q′ might become very large, and we inevitably need to handle remainders in the calculations. The remainder can once again be expressed as ck+s and contributes to the quotient, so (1-1) can be rewritten into the following equation: (abk+ar+bq)k+qr=(abk+ar+bq+⌊kqr​⌋)k+(qrmodk)(1-2) In other words, ⟨a,q⟩⋅⟨b,r⟩=⟨(abk+ar+bq+⌊kqr​⌋)modp,qrmodk⟩ This way, we also ensure that the remainder will be in the range [0,k), and the product of the two numbers will not exceed the range of a 64-bit integer.

179.body: First, consider how to calculate ⌊ka​⌋modp, which is the remainder when ⌊ka​⌋ divided by p. Assume that the quotient of ⌊ka​⌋ divided by p is q and the remainder of ⌊ka​⌋ divided by p is r, and what we are seeking is r. ⌊ka​⌋=qp+r(2-1) According to the division theorem, we have a=⌊ka​⌋⋅k+(amodk)(2-2) Substitute (2-1) into (2-2): a​=(qp+r)⋅k+(amodk)=qpk+rk+(amodk)​ To obtain r, note that a≡rk+(amodk)(modpk) Since rk+(amodk)<rk+k=(r+1)k≤pk, this means the right side is the remainder when a is divided by pk: amodpk=rk+(amodk) Note that the above equation is an equality. Since (amodk)<k, the way to calculate r is to directly divide rk+(amodk) by k, and the quotient is the answer: ⌊krk+(amodk)​⌋=r+⌊kamodk​⌋=r In other words: r=⌊kamodpk​⌋ Returning to the original problem ⌊kxy​⌋modp, according to the above equation: ⌊kxy​⌋modp=⌊kxymodpk​⌋ In practice, when calculating xy, it is modified to take modulo pk to avoid overflow. However, the maximum value of pk is close to the maximum value of the long long range, and in the process of fast exponentiation, __int128 must be used to avoid overflow when multiplying two numbers, yielding incorrect results.

188.body: 雖然用 std::map 存很爽，而且很多諸如 陣列該開多大 、 會不會戳出陣列 、 要怎麼歸零 之類的問題都可以不用擔心，但他畢竟還是多了一個 O(logn) 的複雜度，所以我們還是要試著把他換成更好的資料結構。 不，當然不是用 std::unordered_map。 觀察一下我們每次戳 std::map 的數值範圍是多少 r1：大概是 [0,n] r1 + mn[r1]：大概是 [0,2n] r2 + mn[r2]：大概是 [0,2n] l - K + mx[l] - mn[l]：大概是 [−n,2n]（因為 mx[l] ≥ mn[l]） l - K + mx[l]：大概是 [−n,2n] l1：大概是 [0,n] l1 - mn[l1]：大概是 [−n,n] l2 - mn[l2]：大概是 [−n,n] r + K + mn[r] - mx[r]：大概是 [−n,2n]（因為 mx[r] ≥ mn[r]） r + K - mx[r]：大概是 [−n,2n] 其實根本只會戳到 [−n,2n] 範圍內的東西嘛！那我們根本就可以開一個長度 3n+1 的 std::vector 來取代 std::map，每次要 access 的時候直接平移 n 格用 vec[x + n] 就好了！ 我們已經解決了「陣列該開多大」跟「會不會戳出陣列」的兩個問題了，但「要怎麼歸零」還是沒有解決。沒辦法直接用 for 迴圈歸零，也不能用 std::fill 或 memset 之類的手段（這些都要花 O(n) 的時間來歸零陣列，而不是 O(區間長度)），那我們要怎麼做呢？ 我們可以 回～溯～時～間～ 以上半段計算 Case 1 跟 3 的部分舉例： 我們知道 cnt1[] 根本只會戳 r 的位置， 我們知道 cnt2[] 也根本只會戳 r + A[mn[r]] 的位置， 我們也知道 r1 跟 r2 最後的值是多少了， 所以我們可以在計算完 Case 1 跟 3 之後，把 r2 移回 r1、再把 r1 移回 M 的位置，並在移動的同時在 cnt1[] 跟 cnt2[] 上面反著 減一 ，如此就能在 O(R−L) 時間內清空一個區間了！ 請想想看，為什麼要先移動 r2 再移動 r1？ 時間複雜度：T(n)=2⋅T(n/2)+O(n)⟹T(n)=O(nlogn)。 空間複雜度：O(n)。

193.body: Although using std::map is convenient and many issues like "how big should the array be", "will it go out of bounds", and "how to zero out the array" are not a concern, it still adds an additional O(logn) complexity. So, let's try to replace it with a better data structure. No, it's not using std::unordered_map. Observe how much we poke the std::map r1: Roughly [0,n] r1 + mn[r1]: Roughly [0,2n] r2 + mn[r2]: Roughly [0,2n] l - K + mx[l] - mn[l]: Roughly [−n,2n] (because mx[l] ≥ mn[l]) l - K + mx[l]: Roughly [−n,2n] l1: Roughly [0,n] l1 - mn[l1]: Roughly [−n,n] l2 - mn[l2]: Roughly [−n,n] r + K + mn[r] - mx[r]: Roughly [−n,2n] (because mx[r] ≥ mn[r]) r + K - mx[r]: Roughly [−n,2n] Actually, we only need to access elements within the range of [−n,2n]. Therefore, we can replace std::map with a std::vector of length 3n+1. To access elements, we can simply shift by n and use vec[x + n]. We have addressed the issues of "how large should the array be" and "will it go out of bounds." However, we still need to solve the problem of zeroing out the array. We cannot directly use a for loop to zero out the array, and methods like std::fill or memset are not suitable since they take O(n) time to zero out the entire array, not O(interval length). We can utilize a technique known as backtracking through time . Consider the calculation of Cases 1 and 3 in the first half: We know that cnt1[] only affects the position of r. We know that cnt2[] only affects the position of r + A[mn[r]]. We also know the final values of r1 and r2. After calculating Cases 1 and 3, we can move r2 back to r1 and then move r1 back to the position M. During these movements, we can decrement the values in cnt1[] and cnt2[] in reverse. This process allows us to clear an interval in O(R−L) time! Think about why we need to move r2 before r1. Time complexity: T(n)=2⋅T(n/2)+O(n)⟹T(n)=O(nlogn). Space complexity: O(n).

207.body: When it is possible to defeat a monster with a level of vi​, it implies x≥vi​. After defeating the monster, the new level is x+vi​, and since x+vi​≥vi​+vi​≥vi+1​, it is evident that as long as the initial ability level is greater than that of any monster, one can challenge all monsters. The consideration is to determine the strategy to defeat monsters in the fewest attempts to reach level y. Can you attempt to prove whether it is the optimal strategy to prioritize challenging higher-level monsters first, and if after challenging them the target level (x<y) is still not achieved, then challenge lower-level monsters? Assuming the highest-level monster that can be challenged at the initial level is ℓ2​, the sorted monsters can be divided into two intervals: [ℓ1​,r1​] and [ℓ2​,r2​]. If it is possible to reach the target level by challenging monsters in the second interval, binary search within the second interval to find the monster to challenge (left part of the second interval). If the sum of the second interval cannot meet the target level, then after completing the second interval, switch to binary search within the first interval to find the monster to challenge (right part of the first interval).

A straightforward idea is to treat the queuing students as like they're in a queue data structure, and push the leading element into the back of the queue if the potential pi​ is still positive. One way moves the data, the other moves a pointer, while both are considered efficient enough, as they will iterate through the elements O(∑pi​) times with every transition to the next element a constant time move.

22.body: But how do we keep track of the potentials and know when a student should leave the queue? One way would be to map a student ID to its potential. But since the std::map holds a query time complexity of O(logn), it might not be fast enough as ∑pi​=107, thus anything slower than a linear solution may not work. Some may think of std::unordered_map or hash tables, but though the average time complexity of searching is O(1), the calculations still exceed the time limit. A simple way would to put each students' potential pi​ alongside their IDs in an element (of the queue or list, whatever you might be using). Every time the student is iterated, decrease pi​ by 1. If pi​ turns zero, remove the element. Updating pi​ and removing referred elements are both constant time operations, so we will get O((∑pi​)+n) as the time complexity over these operations.

Additionally, there is a subsequent schedule for the winner of each battle. Define the cost of a schedule c(S′)=∑dS′​[i]×a[i], where dS′​[i] is the maximum number of battles participant i needs to attend in schedule S′. Your task is to find a schedule S such that c(S) is minimized. Output c(S) and describe the corresponding schedule. Based on the description above, a schedule can be considered equivalent to a k-ary tree, where each participant is a leaf node, and dS​[i] represents the depth of each leaf node.

226.body: 仔細觀察題目的敘述，可以將 a[i] 視作 Huffman encoding 中的頻率，dS​[i] 視作編碼的長度。 那麼 k=2 就完全等同於有 n 個字元的 Huffman Encoding 問題。 因此，我們可以像講義中所提到的，將節點中頻率最小的兩個節點 x,y 挑出並組成一個新的節點 z，且其頻率為 x+y。不斷重複，直到節點數 ≤1 。 使用 priority queue 去找到並移除過程中最小頻率的兩個節點 x,y，再將新節點 z 放進去。這過程就等同題目的，挑選 x,y 進行決鬥，決鬥的勝者作為 z 進行剩下的賽程。

227.body: 接著將題目擴展到 k>2，一個直覺的想法是用跟 Subtask 2 一樣的操作，每次從 priority queue 裡面挑出 k 個權重最小的節點，將這些節點的總和作為新節點 z 的權重，最後放回 priority queue。 然而這樣做真的是最好的嗎？套用到 Sample Case 2，會發現得到的答案不是最佳解。 不過稍微觀察，會發現在 n≡1mod(k−1) 的時候 (Subtask 3)，直接挑權重前 k 小的能保證有最佳解。 接著進一步分析，對於最佳的賽程 S ( k 元樹 )，我們能有以下幾個 Claim Claim 1: 所有深度不是最深的節點，其 Sibling 節點的數量必須為 k，且子節點要有兩個以上 可以簡單地觀察出，如果不是的話，將深度更深的節點往上移可以使 c(S) 更小。 Claim 2: 對於任意葉子節點 i,j，若a[i]≤a[j]，則 dS​[i]≥dS​[j] 類似地，如果不是的話，可以將兩葉子節點的位置交換，能使得 c(S) 更小。 Claim 3: 對於任意葉子節點，若將 i 移到同深度的其他位置，答案不變 因為深度一樣，所以任意交換不會影響 c(S) 的結果 透過以上幾點觀察，試著猜出以下的 Greedy 演算法，並證明他是對的 Greedy Algorithm A A(a, k) // a is set of node() S := a cost := 0 while |S| ≠ 1 : Z := new node() Z.childs := ∅ // set of node() Z.val := 0 while |Z.childs| < 2 or |S| % (k - 1) != 0 : // at least 2 in one battle minNode := node with smallest val in S Z.childs = Z.childs ∪ minNode Z.val += minNode.val S := S - minNode cost += Z.val S := S ∪ Z root := the remained node in S return root, cost 證明固定一個 k，對於任意 n 個參賽者，我們用 A 做出來的賽程會是最佳解： 令 Hn​ 是用 A 做出來的賽程，Tn​ 是最佳賽程，我們想證明 c(Hn​)≤c(Tn​)∀a,k 我們可以使用歸納法 base: 1≤n≤k: n=1，不需要進行比賽 n≥2，只需要一場比賽 針對以上兩種狀況，A 顯然能做出最好的賽程。 induction: ∀n<l:c(Hn​)≤c(Tn​)⇒c(Hl​)≤c(Tl​): 對於任意 n<l 的參賽者組合成立，我們都有 c(Hl​)≤c(Tl​) 用反證法證明: 假設存在 Tl​:c(Hl​)>c(Tl​) 我們可以根據Claim 1 & Claim 2 & Claim 3，將 Tl​ 轉成新的賽程 Tl∗​ ，在 Tl∗​ 中權重前 k′ 小的參賽者會參加一場決鬥，其中 k′=k−[(n−1)mod(k−1)]。且 c(Tl​)≥c(Tl∗​) 令 y 為權重前 k′ 小的集合 令 z′ 為權重前 k′ 小的總和 令 a′:=a∪z′−y，∣a′∣=l−k′+1 轉成賽程 Tl∗​ 後，我們能保證 Tl∗​ 一定會存在由 y 組成的一場決鬥；同樣地，按照 A 做出來Hl​ ，也一定會存在由 y 組成的一場決鬥。 我們移除掉在 Tl∗​ 中，由 y 構成的決鬥，變成 Tl−k′+1∗​。可以得到滿足 a′ 的解 直接用 A 對 a′ 做出來的賽程，我們稱為 Hl−k′+1​ 而我們知道 c(Hl​)=c(Hl−k′+1​)+z′;c(Tl∗​)=c(Tl−k′+1∗​)+z′，且因為 c(Hl​)>c(Tl​)≥c(Tl∗​)，所以我們可以推導出 c(Hl−k′+1​)>c(Tl−k′+1∗​) 這與我們的假設 ∀n<l:c(Hn​)≤c(Tn​) 矛盾 因此我們可以知道 c(Hl​)≤c(Tl​)

230.body: By carefully observing the problem description, a[i] can be regarded as frequencies in Huffman encoding, and dS​[i] can be viewed as the length of the encoding. For k=2, this is equivalent to the Huffman Encoding problem with n characters. Therefore, as mentioned in the lecture notes, we can select the two nodes with the smallest frequencies, x and y, and create a new node z with a frequency of x+y. This process is repeated until the number of nodes is less than or equal to 1. Use a priority queue to find and remove the two nodes with the smallest frequencies, x and y, and then insert the new node z. This process is equivalent to selecting x and y for a battle, and the winner continues in the remaining schedule.
230.breadcrumbs: Labs / Term Exams » Lab 3 » C. Pecola or Treat » Subtask 2
230.title: Subtask 2

231.body: Next, extend the problem to k>2. An intuitive approach is to perform similar operations as in Subtask 2. Each time, select k nodes with the smallest weights from the priority queue, use their sum as the weight of the new node z, and finally, insert it back into the priority queue. However, is this truly the best approach? Applying it to Sample Case 2, we find that the obtained answer is not optimal. Yet, with a closer observation, it is noted that when n≡1mod(k−1) (Subtask 3), selecting the smallest k weights directly ensures the optimal solution. Continuing with a more in-depth analysis, for the optimal schedule S (k-ary tree), we have the following claims: Claim 1: For all non-deepest nodes, the number of sibling nodes must be k, and each node must have at least two child nodes. It can be observed that if this is not the case, moving a deeper node up can reduce c(S). Claim 2: For any leaf nodes i and j, if a[i]≤a[j], then dS​[i]≥dS​[j]. Similarly, if not, swapping the positions of the two leaf nodes can reduce c(S). Claim 3: For any leaf node, moving it to another position at the same depth does not change the answer. Since the depth is the same, any exchange does not affect the result of c(S). Based on the observations above, let's attempt to infer the following Greedy algorithm and provide a proof of its correctness. Greedy Algorithm A A(a, k) // a is set of node() S := a cost := 0 while |S| ≠ 1 : Z := new node() Z.childs := ∅ // set of node() Z.val := 0 while |Z.childs| < 2 or |S| % (k - 1) != 0 : // at least 2 in one battle minNode := node with smallest val in S Z.childs = Z.childs ∪ minNode Z.val += minNode.val S := S - minNode cost += Z.val S := S ∪ Z root := the remained node in S return root, cost To prove that for a fixed k, for any n participants, the schedule produced by algorithm A is optimal: Let Hn​ be the schedule produced by A, and Tn​ be the optimal schedule. We want to prove that c(Hn​)≤c(Tn​)∀a,k. We can use induction: Base: 1≤n≤k: For n=1, no competition is needed. For 2≤n≤k, only one competition is needed. In both cases, A can obviously produce the best schedule. Induction: ∀n<l:c(Hn​)≤c(Tn​)⇒c(Hl​)≤c(Tl​): For any combination of participants where n<l, we have c(Hl​)≤c(Tl​). Prove by contradiction: Suppose there exists Tl​:c(Hl​)>c(Tl​). According to Claim 1, Claim 2, and Claim 3, we can transform Tl​ into a new schedule Tl∗​, where the k′ smallest-weight participants participate in a battle, and k′=k−[(n−1)mod(k−1)]. Additionally, c(Tl​)≥c(Tl∗​). Let y be the set of the k′ smallest weights. Let z′ be the sum of the k′ smallest weights. Let a′:=a∪z′−y, ∣a′∣=l−k′+1. After transforming to schedule Tl∗​, we can guarantee that Tl∗​ will have a battle composed of participants from y. Similarly, according to A, the schedule Hl​ will also have a battle composed of participants from y. We remove the battle composed of y in Tl∗​, resulting in Tl−k′+1∗​. This provides a solution satisfying a′. By directly using A to produce the schedule for a′, denoted as Hl−k′+1​, we know that c(Hl​)=c(Hl−k′+1​)+z′;c(Tl∗​)=c(Tl−k′+1∗​)+z′, and because c(Hl​)>c(Tl​)≥c(Tl∗​), we can deduce that c(Hl−k′+1​)>c(Tl−k′+1∗​). This contradicts our assumption ∀n<l:c(Hn​)≤c(Tn​).

240.body: 由於可以重新排列所有元素，大多數人可能會考慮首先將向量 u 和 v 排序，然後再考慮如何排列矩陣 A 以獲得最佳結果。 然後，你可能會遇到一個情況，即矩陣 A 的左上角元素將與向量 u 和 v 中的較大數字相乘，而右下角元素將與二個較小的數字相乘。但如果向量 u 和 v 同時包含正數和負數，那麼左上角的元素將與正的大數字相乘，右下角的元素將負負得正…與正的大數字相乘？ 因此，這個子任務提供了一個簡化的情況，其中所有數字都是非負整數，這樣你就不必擔心這個問題。 理論上，你可以將矩陣 A 的左上角填充為較大的數字，右下角填充為較小的數字，這應該會得到正確的答案。但是，右上角和左下角的元素應該如何填充？ 實際上，我們並不知道如何填充這些元素，但我們希望你可以通過這個子問題來思考：究竟向量 u 和 v 中的數字將如何影響我們填充矩陣 A 的數字。

246.body: Since all elements can be rearranged, most people might consider sorting vectors u and v first and then think about how to arrange matrix A for optimal results. You may encounter a situation where the upper-left element of matrix A will be multiplied by the larger numbers in vectors u and v, while the lower-right element will be multiplied by the two smaller numbers. But if vectors u and v contain both positive and negative numbers, the upper-left element will be multiplied by the positive large number, and the lower-right element will result in a positive product as well. It sounds weird, right? Therefore, this subtask provides a simplified scenario where all numbers are non-negative integers, so you don't have to worry about this issue. In theory, you can fill the upper-left of matrix A with larger numbers and the lower-right with smaller numbers, and this should yield the correct answer. However, how should the elements in the upper-right and lower-left be filled? In reality, we don't know how to fill these elements, but we hope you can think about how the numbers in vectors u and v will affect filling the numbers in matrix A through this subproblem.

255.body: In this subtask, we can visit every node in the beginning, so we only need to determine the precedence of each node. There are only 18 kinds of nodes, consisting of {+1,+2,…,+9} and {x1,x2,…,x9}. Suppose there are several nodes {p1​,p2​,⋯,ph​,m1​,m2​,⋯,mk​}, where pi​ denotes the value of node with '+' sign and mj​ denotes the value of node with 'x' sign. There are three possible scenarios to compare two arbitrary nodes: pi​ vs pj​ wi​ vs wj​ pi​ vs wj​ (Define S as the initial value before doing the below operation) Scenario 1: If we do pi​ first then pj​, the value will be S+pi​+pj​. If we do pj​ first then pi​, the value will be S+pj​+pi​. We can find that the two approaches has no difference, indicating that the priority of arbitrary two addition nodes are the same. Scenario 2: If we do wi​ first then wj​, the value will be S×wi​×wj​. If we do wj​ first then wi​, the value will be S×wj​×wi​. We can find that the two approaches has no difference, indicating that the priority of arbitrary two multiplication nodes are the same. Scenario 3: If we do pi​ first then wj​, the value will be (S+pi​)×wj​=S×wj​+pi​×wj​. If we do wj​ first then pi​, the value will be S×wj​+pi​. We can find that the first approach will always be larger than or equal to the second one, so we can conclude that we always do addition first then do multiplication . In summary, we can sort all nodes by performing addition followed by multiplication, and thereby identify the maximum value for the solution. Note that the from this subtask on, the answer may exceed 1018, so you may use either double or __int128 to record the current answer, whenever the node value exceed 1018, record the value as 1018 and set the inf flag as true**.

256.body: In this subtask, we know that every route has a multiplication node followed by an addition node. However, we cannot use the skill used in Subtask 3 as the addition nodes are "hidden" behind the multiplication node. Luckily, we can observe that whenever a multiplication node is visited, we will definitely visit its following addition node at once due to the conclusion derived in subtask 3 (as it is the only one addition node that can be visited at that time). Therefore, we can “merge” the two nodes in every route. Let’s take the following example: Untitled As mentioned above, it is equivalent to visit a single node with ×3+6 when we choose the first route. So we can combine the original map into the new one below: Untitled So here’s the next question, how to determine the precedence of each node? Same as what we do in subtask 3, we can perform some computation: {×a+b} vs {×c+d} If we do {×a+b} first, then the value will be (si​×a+b)×c+d=(si​×a×c)+(b×c)+d If we do {×c+d} first, then the value will be (si​×c+d)×a+b=(si​×c×a)+(d×a)+b We can find that if (b×c+d)>(d×a+b), we will visit the previous node first. The formula can be further inducted into a relationship formula by rearranging items: →→​(b×c+d)>(d×a+b)(c−1)×b>(a−1)×da−1b​>c−1d​​ Untitled We can calculate the comparing value of each node and determine the order, which is {×1+7},{×2+9},{×3+6}. Finally, the value will be (((1×2)×1+7)×2+9)×3+6=87 In summary, we can sort all the combined nodes by the value of a−1b​ , Note that you have to deal with the edge case a=1 , which has the highest priority as the value of a−1b​ will be infinite. This also meet the conclusion we derived from subtask 3: “addition always has precedence over other nodes”. Note that when you're implementing the compare function, please use the rule (c−1)×b>(a−1)×d instead, as a−1b​>c−1d​ might lead to wrong answer due to incorrect precision of floating point computation.

257.body: In this subtask, each route might have several multiplication nodes, so it might be hard to decide which route to traverse if you only take the first merged multiplication node into consideration (since there might be a better merged multiplication hidden behind). We will introduce a little trick here. Just like what you did to merge addition node into multiplication node, we can also merge multiplication node into another one. Therefore, we can merge all the nodes into a single node in the order of a−1b​. So here’s the question, how to merge two merged multiplication nodes? Merge {×c+d} into {×a+b} Which means you do {×a+b} first then do {×c+d}, the value will be (si​×a+b)×c+d=si​×(a×c)+(b×c+d) That’s right! you will find that you get a node with {×(ac)+(bc+d)}. After you merge the two nodes, don’t forget to add this new node value into the priority queue to update its order (the comparing value of this node is ac−1bc+d​) Let’s take the following example: Untitled In the beginning, we calculate the comparing value of each node. Untitled Merge node of value inf into its parent and reassign the parent of its child to its parent. Untitled Recalculate the comparing value of each value and determine which node to be chosen. The merged node will be {×(2×3)+(0×3+9)}={×6+9}. Untitled The next node selected should be node 1; however, it has nothing to merge, so we just simply ignore it. Instead, we take {×3+5},{×6+9},{×2} in order. Finally we will get a node (((si​×2+4)×3+5)×6+9)×2=si​×72+222 , which is {×72+111}. Then we can calculate the answer 1×72+222=294.

The state definition of the problem is as follows: dp[i][j]=the length of the LCS of a[1…i] and b[1…j]dp[i][j]=max⎩⎨⎧​i′≤i and j′≤j(i′,j′)=(i,j)​max​{dp[i′][j′]},i′<i and j′<jmax​{dp[i′][j′]}+1,​if we don’t pair a[i] with b[j]if a[i]=b[j] and we pair a[i] with b[j]​​ Since dp[i][j]≥dp[i′][j′] for all i′≤i and j′≤j, dp[i−1][j] and dp[i][j−1] dominates all other options in the first case, and dp[i−1][j−1] dominates all other options in the second case. 37.body: According to the problem statement, our goal is to find the maximum distance between two adjacent jubutsus whenever a new jubutsu is added. A simple idea is to keep track of the distances between each adjacent jubutsu, and by finding the largest distance and dividing the distance by 2 , the answer could be obtained (where we can place a new shikigami). 38.body: The most straightforward approach is to iterate through every jubutsu to find the maximum distance whenever a new jubutsu is added. However, for each newly added jubutsu, it would take us O(k) time to search, where k is the total number of jubutsus at the moment. This algorithm would result in an O(1+2+3+⋯+n)=O(n2) time complexity, which is not efficient enough.

By using efficient data structures, we can reduce the total complexity from O(n2) to O(nlogn).

52.body: 只有刪除最大値跟加入 MEX 兩種操作。 Case 1: 如果序列裡的數字是從零開始的連續非負整數們，那刪除 max 跟加入 MEX 都會變得很單純，只會動到序列的最後一個數字而已。 max{0,1,2,…,k}=k MEX{0,1,2,…,k}=k+1 Case 2: 如果序列裡的數字還不是從零開始的連續非負整數們（有洞），那刪除 max 跟加入 MEX 的數字們就還不會有交集。 證明很單純：假設 k 是最大的 <an−1​ 且沒出現在 a 裡面的數字。那刪除 max 會去把 an−1​ 刪掉，而加入 MEX 會把一個 ≤k<an−1​ 的數字加進去（補洞）。 於是，可以維護一個變數紀錄上一次的 MEX 值是多少： 只要這個值還小於序列 a 的長度，就代表還有洞要補，而這次的 MEX 也一定會比上一次的還要大。 當這個值等於序列 a 的長度時就會變成 Case 1。

53.body: 現在多了刪最小値的操作，相當於是在後院鑿洞，上個子任務存在的 MEX 遞增的性質也被破壞掉了。不如直接換個思路？ 把相鄰的數字「黏」在一起當成一個區間，這樣在算 MEX 的時候就可以一次跳過一整段數字。 因為跳過一段數字就會掉進一個洞裡，所以其實跳一次就會直接得到答案了！ 刪最小値、刪最大値的操作也仍然只是修改第一個或最後一個區間的端點。 舉個例子：假設在這個子任務依序進行以下操作，那麼會長這樣： Empty (Insert MEX(S)) →[0,0] (Insert MEX(S)) →[0,1] (Insert MEX(S)) →[0,2] (Insert MEX(S)) →[0,3] (Insert MEX(S)) →[0,4] (Remove min(S)) →[1,4] (Remove min(S)) →[2,4] (Remove min(S)) →[3,4] (Insert MEX(S)) →[0,0],[3,4] (Remove max(S)) →[0,0],[3,3] (Remove min(S)) →[3,3] (Insert MEX(S)) →[0,0],[3,3] (Insert MEX(S)) →[0,1],[3,3] (Insert MEX(S)) →[0,3] 如果在刪除時把區間整個刪除了就移除、查詢 MEX 就是看第一個區間包不包含 0： 包含 0 時 MEX 就會是該區間的右界 +1。 不包含 0 時 MEX 就會是 0。 實作上需要注意當相鄰兩個區間接觸到彼此就需要將其合併，而這只會發生在前兩個區間。

Case 1: If the numbers in the sequence are consecutive non-negative integers starting from zero, deleting max and adding MEX become simple, affecting only the last number in the sequence. max{0,1,2,…,k}=k MEX{0,1,2,…,k}=k+1 Case 2: If the sequence contains non-consecutive non-negative integers (has gaps), numbers of deleting max and adding of MEX will not intersect. Therefore, maintain a variable to record the last MEX value: As long as this value is less than the length of the sequence a, there are still gaps to fill, and the added MEX will be greater than the previous one. 71.body: 現在考慮「沒有重複的點，但 y 座標可能相同」的情況。對這些點應該用什麼順序掃過去才能讓上面的作法正確呢？ 作法 y 座標相同就按照 x 座標由大到小排序。因為在 y 相同的時候 x 小的會包含 x 大的，所以我們要先將 x 較大的加入 S 才能正確地判斷。 現在考慮「有重複的點」的情況。對這些點應該用什麼順序掃過去才能讓上面的作法正確呢？ 作法 無論是什麼順序都會有一個問題：第一個掃到的點一定不會檢查到其他的點。 但透過觀察到重複點的答案一定是 True，我們可以在排序後先判斷這個點是否跟下個點相同來決定這個點的答案是不是 True，不相同的情況下再去檢查 S 中的 x 座標最大值的點。 能證明所有的情況都會被考慮到（a.k.a. 演算法的正確性）嗎？ Proof. 觀察平面上兩點的關係，可以分為以下三種情況： y 座標相異 y 座標相同、x 座標相異 x, y 座標皆相同 這三種情況包含了所有兩點之間的關係，而在上面的做法中我們已經對這三種情況都做出了正確的處理，因此所有的情況都會被考慮到。 這個演算法的時間複雜度是多少？ Proof. 排序的時間複雜度是 O(nlogn)，而之後的掃描線只會對每個點做 O(1) 次檢查，因此時間複雜度是 O(nlogn)。

74.body: Imagine a line sweeping from bottom to top. Whenever it encounters a point, it adds it to a set S. For convenience, let's first assume all points have different y coordinates. To know if there is a point at the bottom right of (ℓ,r), we need to check if there's a point in S whose x coordinate is greater than ℓ and whose y coordinate is less than r. And when we reach a point (ℓ,r) during the sweep, we already know that all points previously in S have y coordinates less than r. So, if we can quickly find if there exists a point in S with x coordinate ≥ℓ, we'll know if (ℓ,r) contains any other points. Please note, we don't need to know which points are in S, we just need to know if there's a point in S whose x coordinate is larger than ℓ. If you still plan to store these points in a std::set or check them one by one, please revisit the sentence in red above. Answer Just use a variable to keep track of the largest x coordinate in S.

75.body: Now consider the case where "there are no duplicate points, but y coordinates may be the same." What order should we use to sweep over these points to make the above method work correctly? Answer If the y coordinates are the same, sort by x coordinates in descending order. This is because, with the same y, the one with a smaller x will contain the one with a larger x. So, we should add the one with a larger x to S first to make the judgment correctly. Now consider the situation where "there are duplicate points." What order should we use to sweep these points to make the method above work correctly? Answer Regardless of the order, there will always be an issue: the first point swept won't be able to check other points. However, by noticing that the answer for duplicate points will definitely be True, we can decide if this point's answer is True by checking if it is the same as the next point after sorting. If not, we then check the point with the maximum x coordinate in S. Can you prove that all cases are considered (a.k.a. the correctness of the algorithm)? Proof. Observing the relationship between two points on the plane, we can divide it into three scenarios: Different y coordinates. Same y coordinates, different x coordinates. Both x and y coordinates are the same. These three scenarios cover all possible relationships between two points. The method above has addressed all these scenarios correctly, so all cases are considered. What is the time complexity of this algorithm? Proof. The time complexity for sorting is O(nlogn), and the subsequent sweep line only checks each point O(1) times, so the overall time complexity is O(nlogn).

Suppose we position k in a certain (i,j) and assess whether it's possible to fill the table under this circumstance. (i,j)=(3,2) After some try, you may discover that it's impossible to fill. Because we found there's 5 blocks need to have a number smaller than 5, but we only have 4 distinct value smaller than 5. Figure 2: (i,j)=(3,2) (i,j)=(1,2) Similar to the case above, it's impossible to find a fill method in this case. Because there's 5 blocks need to have a number greater than 5, but we only have 4 distinct value greater then 5. Figure 3: (i,j)=(1,2) After experimenting, you might realize that filling is unfeasible in some scenarios because there are either too few numbers smaller or larger than k for the required blocks. To generalize the observation, we contemplate a fixed (i,j) and recognize the constraints for the numbers surrounding it, ensuring there are enough smaller or larger numbers. Upper-left conner of (i,j) Blocks which value must smaller than T(i,j) is ij−1. Numbers smaller than k is k−1. Therefore, for k to be placed at (i,j), we must have k−1≥ij−1. Bottom-right conner of (i,j) Blocks which value must greater than T(i,j) is (n−i+1)(m−j+1)−1. Numbers greater than k is mn−k. Therefore, for k to be placed at (i,j), we must have mn−k≥(n−i+1)(m−j+1)−1. After some try, you may find that we can only use these two inequalities to validate that number k can or can not be placed on (i,j). But is these two inequality really enough? Let's consider a general way to fill when both inequality holds. If both inequalities hold, a standard method for filling emerges, suggesting not to waste numbers and fill the upper left and bottom right corners first, followed by the remaining spaces. Step 1 Step 2 Step 3 Step 1: fill the upper-left conner of (i,j) with [1,ij−1]. Step 2: fill the bottom-right conner of (i,j) with [mn−(n−i+1)(m−j+1)+2,mn] Step 3: fill the remaining part with the remaining numbers. Since both of the inequality holds, there must have enough numbers for Step 1 and Step 2 to fill in. And since the remaining numbers is greater than ij−1 and is less than mn−(n−i+1)(m−j+1)+2, there's no need to consider the border of left upper part (yellow part) and right bottom part (green part). 96.body: The upper convex polygon has several nice properties, such as: From left to right, the slope of each edge shows a decreasing trend. For each point on the upper convex polygon, although there are infinitely many tangents that can pass through it, note that the slopes of these tangents are bounded by the slopes of the adjacent sides of the point. Combining the above two points, we can find that the slope of the tangents for each point will show a decreasing trend from left to right. When you query with a tangent slope m and receive a result (x,y), you can make the following inferences: x=k; then you've found the y you need! x<k; unfortunately, but since you know point k is on the right, you should use a smaller m to query point k. x>k; conversely, you should use a larger m to query point k. We can adjust the slope to make the tangent we query approach the point required by the problem. Theoretically, as we get closer to (k,y[k]), the slope we use will be closer to the slope of the tangent passing through (k,y[k]). Because the slope of the tangents only appears between [−109,109], and we can only query 32 times, trying each slope one by one definitely won't grant you AC. Therefore, we need to use the inferences mentioned above to quickly narrow down the range of tangent slopes and thereby lock the tangent point on k. If we want to minimize the range of slopes as much as possible with a single query, what should we ask? Asking too close to the edge often makes it impossible to narrow down the range; always asking about the midpoint of a range ensures that the range is reduced by half each time!

98.body: In situations where three points lie on the same line, the point k you're looking for might be on the same tangent line as other points. We assume that among the points that share a tangent line with point k, the one farthest to the left has coordinates (ℓ,y[ℓ]), and the slope of the tangent line is m. If you directly use the program mentioned above on the test data described, the final point you find will not be the answer, but rather (ℓ,y[ℓ]). On a two-dimensional plane, you only need one point on the line (ℓ,y[ℓ]) and the slope of the line m to uniquely determine the equation of the line: y−y[ℓ]=m(x−ℓ) Since (k,y[k]) is also on the line, it can be substituted into the equation, maintaining equality: y[k]−y[ℓ]=m(k−ℓ) After rearranging, we get: y[k]=y[ℓ]+m(k−ℓ) This way, you can calculate the answer.

Similarly, using the last round of queries in a binary search doesn't guarantee that what's being queried is lo. This means that relying on the value of mi in the final iteration might lead to incorrect results, as it might not reflect the exact point where the condition changes (which is what we are often looking for in a binary search). This common oversight occurs because programmers might assume the middle value reflects the current low or high bound at the end of the binary search, but that's not always the case. Care needs to be taken to use the correct bounds in the condition checking and when finalizing the result of the binary search.
